observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following to Management:

Conduct the physical inventory count for real properties;

The GSO and the Municipal Accountant undertake the necessary procedures to reconcile their records based on the result of the physical count;

The GSO prepare Property Cards (PCs) for items of PPEs found at station and ensure that the PCs are updated by posting all unrecorded acquisition/receipt, issue/transfer and disposal of PPE, if any;

The Municipal Accountant to make constant communication with the GSO and the Inventory Committee in order to establish an accurate and reliable PPE balances in the FS; and

The LCE to require all concerned officials/ committees to complete the necessary procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in order to establish an accurate and reliable PPE balances in the FS.

We recommended the following to Management:

Provide specific timeline for the period of implementation of the PPAs;

Refrain from providing generic/lump sum appropriations in the Annual Budget and AIP, instead, identify and indicate specific PPAs;

Ensure that PPAs to be funded out of the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and -implementation-ready; and

Conduct review and evaluation of PPAs and consider changes/realignments in the budget for projects which cannot be implemented or have residual balances during the year to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the SB.

We recommended the following to management:

The PSDS/LSB Co-Chairperson to request a copy of the RQA effective during the time of hiring to validate the responses provided by some local paid teachers that they are already included in the RQA and submit the same to the Audit Team;
The LSB to submit the list of elementary and secondary schools identified to have shortages per the teacher deployment analysis of DepEd or any document to support the need of hiring teacher chargeable against the SEF;
Submit the copy of the LSB minutes of meeting, if any, showing that the provision of DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017, particularly the requirement of utilizing the RQA, were properly deliberated and considered, and submit any document showing prior approval from proper authority to support the hiring teachers who were not in the RQA, if any; and
Submit a written justification on hiring teachers charged against the SEF who were not in the RQA.

We recommended the following to management:

Submit pertinent documents in relation to the recorded parcels of land without any ownership documents;

Submit copy of SB Resolution authorizing the former local chief executive to enter into a Deed of Absolute Sale in behalf of the LGU in relation to the acquired lot amounting to P227,376.00 located in Barangay Kagawasan, Dimataling ZdS (located in Barangay Sugbay Uno as per Tax Declaration) or any other document that will show that it is the LGU who acquired the said property;

Submit additional data and/or information pertaining to the unrecorded 6 parcels of land with TCT in the name of the LGU to facilitate the recording of the said properties in the books of accounts.

We recommended the following to management:

Submit a copy of the Registry of Public Infrastructure;

Create a sub-committee or group under the Municipal Inventory Committee, provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The Municipal Engineer, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The GSO render the Report of Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period and maintain the following:
1. Local Road Inventory and Road Map
2. Complete Local Road Network Property Card for all records and its components (Annex E of COA Circular No. 2015-008); and

The Municipal Accountant provide adjusting journal entries to recognize changes upon completion of the required inventory reports and reconciliation with the Registry of Public Infrastructure and prepare and maintain the following:
1. Subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network
2. Lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road networks at the end of the year.

Recommendation
We recommended the following:
The Office of the GSO and the Inventory Committee to immediately convene and conduct complete physical count on the PPE;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant, Office of the GSO and the Inventory Committee to immediately convene and conduct full reconciliation on the accounting records with the results of the actual physical count based on the RPCPPE;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Office of the Auditor a reconciled PPELC on all PPE accounts after the results of the reconciliation;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant and the Office of the GSO to strictly follow the procedures for the disposition of non-existing/missing PPEs provided in Items 7 and 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
The Office of the Municipal Mayor to strictly monitor the full implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE.

Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to the following:
The Office of the Municipal Mayor to issue an Executive Order reconstituting the Disposal Committee to update the composition of the Disposal Committee;
The GSO and the Disposal Committee to attend trainings and seminars in the conduct of disposal of government properties in line with the new issuance of the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties;
The Disposal Committee to follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of disposal of unserviceable property provided in the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties; and
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to draw journal entries on the derecognition of the unserviceable properties after disposal in the books and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor.

Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed on the following:
The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant with the duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible for the year to serve as basis for setting up the RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred Credits at the beginning of the year;
The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant of a duly certified list showing the names of delinquent taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible;
The Municipal Accountant trace the entries made to reconcile the difference between the amount of the recorded RPT and SET Receivables and related Deferred RPT/SET accounts; and
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer reconcile their records to present reliable RPT and SET Receivables in the FS.

Recommendation
We recommended the following:
The concerned offices to submit explanation to the Audit Team on the existence of unremitted contributions and/or loan amortizations of Philhealth and GSIS;
The concerned offices to immediately conduct reconciliation on its existing records pertaining to membership contributions and/or loan payments to ensure exact and accurate amounts for withholding and remittance;
Immediately remit to the Philhealth and the GSIS, the prior periods’ unremitted contributions of the LGU employees; and
Ensure full and timely withholding and remittance of monthly contributions in accordance with the schedule of payments prescribed by the said government corporations to avoid penalties.

We recommended the following to Management:

The Municipal Treasurer coordinate with the Municipal Accountant for purposes of reconciliation, review his records and make necessary adjustment to correct the noted deficiencies in order to have an updated and correct balances of cash in the cashbooks;

The Municipal Treasurer prepare his RCD to report his own collections and remittances from the Liquidating Officer, and record the same in the appropriate cashbooks;

The Municipal Treasurer avoid force balancing records just to reconcile with the balances of the accounting unit. Beginning balance for the year be based on the ending balance of the prior year;

The Municipal Treasurer ensure compliance with the procedures on recording and reporting collections provided in the NGAS Manual for LGUs;

The Municipal Treasurer record only collections in the cashbooks for cash local treasury with actual cash received;

The Municipal Accountant review the entry for the SEF collection in the month of November 2023 and make necessary adjustment if warranted; and

The LCE direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile regularly their respective cash records to detect instantly any errors made in the process.

We recommended the following to Management:

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant implement the procedures as provided under Section 59 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 on Spoiled and Stale Checks;

The Municipal Accountant inform the Municipal Treasurer in writing about the stale checks noted in the Bank Reconciliation Statement;

The Municipal Treasurer determine the status of the Stale Checks and prepare a report showing as to whether the checks were already claimed by the payee or are still unreleased and on hand;

The Municipal Treasurer send communication to the concerned payee informing him/her on the status of the check. If the concerned payee appeared to claim the check or requested for a re-issuance of the stale check, the Municipal Treasurer issue a new check to the claimant in accordance with the procedures provided under Section 59 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 on Spoiled and Stale Checks; and

After exhaustion of the communication phase and the check still remained unclaimed in the possession of the Municipal Treasurer, the latter submit the necessary documents to the Municipal Accountant for the recording of the corresponding payable.

We recommended the following to Management:

All Accountable Officers (AOs) remit/deposit all collections intact daily or at the close of each business day and for collectors assigned to the field, where travel time from their places of assignment to the Treasurer’s Office is more than one day, turnover of collections be made at least once a week or as soon as the collections reach P5,000.00;

The Liquidating Officer perform proper verification procedures as prescribed in the manual and sign only the RCD after checking that all entries are correct and properly verified with;

The Accountable Form Custodian only release new accountable forms after ensuring that previously issued accountable forms are properly accounted for and collections from which are duly remitted to the Liquidating Officer;

Consider the maintenance of individual records or folder for each AO to facilitate proper and efficient monitoring of collections, remittances and accountable forms; and

If possible, designate an Accountable Forms Custodian who does not perform collecting function.

We recommended the following to Management:

Check and verify the bank accounts with balances which are non-moving and consider the closing of the same, if warranted;

Refrain from providing generic/lump sum appropriations in the Annual Budget and AIP, instead, identify and indicate specific PPAs;

Ensure that PPAs to be funded out of the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and -implementation-ready; and

Conduct review and evaluation of PPAs and consider changes/realignments in the budget for projects which cannot be implemented or have residual balances during the year to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the SB.

We recommended the following to management:

Assess its existing organizational structure in order to establish the ideal number of plantilla thereby avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job order personnel;

Hiring of job order personnel be resorted to base on necessity, as prescribed in Section 76 of R.A. 7160, thus formulate a policy or manual on hiring of contract of services and job orders in order to avoid waste of government funds;

Stipulate clearly and specifically in the job order contracts the scope of duties and functions to be performed in order to prevent the performance of duties and functions which are identical or part of the job description of existing regular employees; and

We recommended the following to management:

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommend that the LCE institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

a) To conduct risk assessment; 
b) To identify critical processes and functions;
c) To determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
d) To conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e) To formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and 
f) To submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended the following to management:


Maintain the practice of sending demand letters to employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to settle unliquidated CAs and do the same on a regular basis;

For unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are still in active service and after receiving the demand letters, still failed to settle their obligation nor made an appropriate justification, immediately withhold their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;

Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters; and

Require the Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official and employee and report the status of their liquidations to the Local Chief Executive on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter.

